Facial Emotion Detection

Executive summary

The Facial Emotion Recognition Project aims to develop a robust neural network model capable of accurately detecting and classifying emotions from facial images into one of four emotions, Happy, Neutral, Sad and Surprise. Emotion recognition has wide-ranging applications across various industries, including healthcare, marketing, and human-computer interaction.

The project began with augmenting the pre-collected data, including gathering a diverse dataset of facial images representing the four different emotions. Augmenting techniques were applied to the data to shear, flip and resize the images for better training.

Next, a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) architecture was designed and trained using the preprocessed dataset. The CNN model leverages the spatial hierarchies present in facial images to automatically learn discriminative features for emotion classification. Training the model involved optimizing hyperparameters, such as learning rate, batch size, and network architecture, to achieve the best performance. Performance was measured using the training and validation accuracy which was simultaneous to the training

After training, test datasets were used to assess its accuracy, precision, recall and F1-score. The confusion matrix was plotted to compare the actual and predicted results

The final trained model demonstrated promising results, achieving a test accuracy of 74%. However, ongoing monitoring and refinement of the model are essential to address potential biases, adapt to new data distributions, and maintain optimal performance in real-world settings.

In conclusion, the Facial Emotion Recognition Project represents a significant advancement in leveraging artificial intelligence for emotion analysis from facial expressions. By accurately detecting and classifying emotions, the model opens up opportunities for improving human-computer interaction, personalized marketing strategies, mental health assessment, and more. Continued research and development in this field have the potential to unlock even greater value and impact in the future.

Out of all the different models and their variants tested, it is found that Model 3 performs the best in terms of:

-Training accuracy - 72%

-Validation accuracy - 71%

-Test accuracy -77%

-Average F1 score (among 4 classes)-76%

Problem and solution summary

Summary of the problem

Recognising facial emotions is important to understand human behaviour, to ease human-computer interaction, in healthcare especially mental health conditions, security and surveillance to detect abnormal behaviour, in education for assessing student behaviour and enhance learning outcomes. It can also be used in market research and advertising to understand customer experience. Due to these widespread business implications, this is an important problem to solve. Our problem here is to develop a deep learning model that can predict the emotion in an image as one of 'Happy', 'Neutral', 'Sad', 'Surprise'.

Solution Summary

After unzipping and extracting the images, few of the images from each class were viewed and the distribtution of the classes plotted. It was found that there was a slight imbalance in the classes. The 'Surprise' was found to have fewer number of images. This was ignored as it didn't pose a serious threat to the performance.

4 types of models were designed,trained and tested:

-Basic-A model with a minimum number of Convolutional and fully connected layers was designed and tested. Of the RGB and grayscale models trained and tested,grayscale performed better

-This basic grayscale model was improved by adding dropout layers and batch normalization to combat overfitting

-Transfer learning models, VGG16,ResNet and EfficientNet models were combined with RGB input layers, of which ResNet performed the best. This model did not have an accuracy comparable to the improved basic model that was developed earlier. It was concluded that transfer learning models worl best when the input images are RGB as they are designed for RGB images

-A deeper Neural Network with more number of Conv2D layers was designed with grayscale input, trained and tested. This model gave the best accuracy. The CNN model was chosen as the final model as it was found to have:

-Higher training accuracy

-Higher validation accuracy

-Higher training accuracy

-Reduced overfitting

-Comparativerly lower confusion between the emotions, especially 'Sad' and 'Neutral'

-Higher F1 score for all classes

Building a Complex Neural Network Architecture

The best performing model building details can be found below:

Model Building

Model 3 specifications are as follows:

First Convolutional Layer with 32 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and input_shape=(48,48,1) for grayscale input and activation='relu'

Second Convolutional Layer with 32 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Third Convolutional Layer with 64 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Fourth Convolutional Layer with 64 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Fifth Convolutional Layer with 64 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Sixth Convolutional Layer with 64 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Maxpooling layer of 2,2

Seventh Convolutional Layer with 128 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Eighth Convolutional Layer with 128 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Ninth Convolutional Layer with 128 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Tenth Convolutional Layer with 128 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Maxpooling layer of 2,2

Eleventh Convolutional Layer with 256 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Twelfth Convolutional Layer with 256 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Thirteenth Convolutional Layer with 256 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Fourteenth Convolutional Layer with 256 filters, kernel size=4, padding='same' and activation='relu'

Maxpooling layer of 2,2

Flatten()

First dropout layer with rate=0.2

BatchNormalization

Dense layer with 32 nodes and activation='relu'

Second dropout layer with rate=0.2

BatchNormalization

Dense layer with 32 nodes and activation='relu'

Dense layer with 4 output nodes with activation='Softmax' for the 4 different emotions to be predicted

The model was compiled with Adam Optimizer with a learning rate of 0.001

In[16]:
model3=Sequential()

model3.add(Conv2D(32,(4,4),activation='relu',padding='same',input_shape=(48,48,1)))  #moving ahead with grayscale inputs as RGB didnt show much big of a difference
model3.add(Conv2D(32,(4,4),activation='relu',padding='same'))

model3.add(Conv2D(64,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))                        #removed maxpooling layers
model3.add(Conv2D(64,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))                        #2 layers of conv2D with 64 filters and kernel size increased to (4,4) to capture bigger details


model3.add(Conv2D(64,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))                        #removed maxpooling layers
model3.add(Conv2D(64,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))                        #2 layers of conv2D with 64 filters and kernel size increased to (4,4) to capture bigger details
model3.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))

model3.add(Conv2D(128,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))                       #2 layers of conv2D with 128 filters
model3.add(Conv2D(128,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))


model3.add(Conv2D(128,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))                       #2 layers of conv2D with 128 filters
model3.add(Conv2D(128,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))
model3.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))

model3.add(Conv2D(256,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))                       #2 layers of conv2D with 256 filters
model3.add(Conv2D(256,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))


model3.add(Conv2D(256,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))                       #2 layers of conv2D with 256 filters
model3.add(Conv2D(256,(4,4),padding='same',activation='relu'))
model3.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))

model3.add(Flatten())

model3.add(Dropout(0.2))                                              #to correct the overfitting that may be caused
model3.add(BatchNormalization())

model3.add(Dense(32,activation='relu'))
model3.add(Dropout(0.2))                                              #to correct the overfitting that may be caused
model3.add(BatchNormalization())

model3.add(Dense(32,activation='relu'))

model3.add(Dense(4,activation="Softmax"))

model3.summary()

Impact on Business

A facial emotion recognition model with a 77% test accuracy can have high business utility in different sectors including education, health, safety and security,communications and much more. Being able to effectively predict human emotions can the pave way for easier human-machine interactions further leading towards technological breakthroughs.

Recommendations for implementation

Design reccomendations

A device consisting a minimum of 10 MP camera that can capture the face is recommended.

-Input images must be in the form of grayscale images. If they are coloured they must be converted to RGB prior to being input into the model for prediction

-Input image size must be 48 x 48. If not, it must be resized to fit this dimension as the model is designed to accept images of this size

-Dimensions of the image should be adjusted to account for batch_size=1. The image size would then be (1,48,48,1),ie,(batch_size=1 correction,48x48 image size,1-gray_scale). This is because our model accepts input in batches of 1.

-The predicted output of the model is in the form of an array of probabilities. This must be converted to the label using the below criteria using np.argmax() function or a substitute based on the platform:

-Index 0:Happy

-Index 1:Neutral

-Index 2:Sad

-Index 3:Surprise

Key Actionables for Stakeholders

-Designing and implementing an interface: A user interface must be designed which will be able to get an image from a user and output the result returned by the model to the user interface. This needs to be done in collaboration with an IT team.

-Integrating the model into the desired application: Facial Emotion recognition systems are usually part of other larger systems. So, integrating the system into the larger system must be planned and executed. This could be a cloud platform, hand held devices or edge servers. This again needs to be done in collaboration with an IT team

-Ethical issues must be considered as we now have the capability to predict facial emotions without necessarily having the consent of the owners of the face. We need to make sure that the consent of a person is taken prior to being used as the input for the system

-End users must be given sufficient training and support for using the system if required.

-Feedback to be given for improvement of model performance as model development is a continuous process.

Risks and Challenges

As the model has an accuracy of 77%, there will be times when there are incorrect predictions, precisely speaking, 23% of the time. Strategies must be in place to tackle such situations.

Low computation power: If the machine used to train the model has a very low computation power, it could lead to low model performance

Further Analysis and Associated problems

The model accuracy can be increased if we train it on more images from the 'sad' and 'neutral' class.

A deeper fully connected network can also be implemented at the cost of computational resources.

Our final model deals only with 4 human emotions. Training the model on more emotions, for eg, 'Angry', 'Disgust',etc ,can expand its applications to more business sectors.

Other findings

If the training data images are gray scale, you get better performance with grayscale input models

Transfer learning models VGG16, ResnetV2 and EfficientNet accept RGB inputs and don't perform well with grayscale images

Setting Shuffle=True improves training accuracy greatly

Increasing the number of Conv2D layers improves performance of the model

Testing the model on custom images with the help of a temporary GUI in Collab
